MEMORY SIZING

* In the case of Sparrow it is much easier
* just read from location $FFFF8006, this will set up the memory
* controller automatically.  The register looks like this:
* 8006 Read only vvmm rrbf
*
*			f - 0 - 0 wait state DRAMS
*			    1 - 1 wait state DRAMS
*			b - 0 - 16 bit video bus
*			    1 - 32 bit video bus
*		       rr - 00 - 0 wait state ROMS
*			    01 - 1 wait state ROMS
*			    10 - 1 wait state ROMS
*			    11 - reserved
*		       mm - 00 - 256K deep DRAM
*			    01 - 1M deep DRAM
*			    10 - 4M deep DRAM
*			    11 - reserved
*		       vv - 00 - VGA monitor
*			    01 - ST monochrome monitor
*			    10 - ST colot monitor
*			    11 - TV
* Note that the vv bits are for information only, they do not actually affect
* the hardware in any way.  The other bits are actually used by the hardware
* to set itself up.
*
* To determine memory size:
* Memory size is depth of DRAM times width of bus divided by 8.
* Memory size is (256*1024)*(4^mm)*(b+1)*2 in bytes.
* I guess that a table is better the writting pow().
* Further note: The maximum RAM that is useable is 14M so the max config
* of 16M must be clamped to 14M.

Table for memory size:

	mm b	size
	00 0	512K
	00 1	1M
	01 0	2M
	01 1	4M
	10 0	8M
	10 1	14M
	11 x	illegal

Or, (512K << mmb) capped to 14MB.

Initialization:

	move.w	SPAR_CONF,d0	; auto-config memory controller
	lsr.w	#8,d0		; get switches in low word: d0=vvmmrrbf
	lsr.b	#1,d0		; d0=vvmmrrb
	move.b	d0,d1
	and.b	#1,d1		; just keep low bit -- d1=b
	lsr.b	#2,d0		; d0=vvmmr
	and.b	#6,d0		; d0=00mm0
	or.b	d0,d1		; d1=00mmb
	move.l	#$80000,d0	; 512KB
	asl.l	d1,d0		; 512K << d1 is the memory size
	cmp.b	#5,d1		; unless mmb was 5
	bne	gotmem		; (no)
	move.l	#1024*1024*14,d0	; ...in which case we cap at 14MB.
gotmem:	move.l	d0,d5		; d5 is phystop

